=========================================================
C++ MULTITHREADING INTERVIEW NOTES (BEGINNER TO INTERVIEW)
=========================================================

=========================================================
1. WHAT IS A THREAD?
=========================================================

A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process.

Process:
    Application running in memory.

Thread:
    Execution path inside a process.

Example:
    Chrome Browser
        Process
           ├── UI Thread
           ├── Rendering Thread
           ├── Network Thread
           └── Worker Thread

Benefits:
- Better CPU utilization
- Parallel execution
- Faster applications
- Responsive UI

=========================================================
2. PROCESS VS THREAD
=========================================================

Process:
- Independent memory
- Heavyweight
- Expensive creation

Thread:
- Share process memory
- Lightweight
- Faster creation

=========================================================
3. C++11 MULTITHREADING SUPPORT
=========================================================

Header:

#include <thread>

Main classes:

std::thread
std::mutex
std::lock_guard
std::unique_lock
std::condition_variable
std::atomic
std::future
std::promise

=========================================================
4. CREATE A THREAD
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

void work()
{
    std::cout << "Worker Thread\n";
}

int main()
{
    std::thread t(work);

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

=========================================================
5. join()
=========================================================

Waits for thread completion.

t.join();

Main thread blocks until worker thread finishes.

Interview:
Q: What happens if join() is not called?

A:
Program terminates if thread object is destroyed while thread is still joinable.

=========================================================
6. detach()
=========================================================

Separates thread from thread object.

t.detach();

Thread runs independently.

Interview:
Q: When should detach be avoided?

A:
When thread accesses resources that may get destroyed.

=========================================================
7. JOINABLE THREAD
=========================================================

if(t.joinable())
{
    t.join();
}

Checks whether thread owns execution thread.

=========================================================
8. PASS ARGUMENTS TO THREAD
=========================================================

void print(int x)
{
    std::cout << x;
}

std::thread t(print, 10);

t.join();

