11. WHAT IS A RACE CONDITION?
=========================================================

Multiple threads access shared data simultaneously
and at least one modifies it.

Example:

int counter = 0;

Thread1:
counter++;

Thread2:
counter++;

Expected:
2

Actual:
1 or 2

Result unpredictable.

=========================================================
12. CRITICAL SECTION
=========================================================

Code accessing shared resource.

Example:

counter++;

Must be protected.

=========================================================
13. WHAT IS MUTEX?
=========================================================

Mutex = Mutual Exclusion

Allows only one thread at a time to access
critical section.

Header:

#include <mutex>

=========================================================
14. BASIC MUTEX EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>

std::mutex mtx;

int counter = 0;

void increment()
{
    for(int i=0;i<100000;i++)
    {
        mtx.lock();

        counter++;

        mtx.unlock();
    }
}

=========================================================
15. PROBLEM WITH lock()/unlock()
=========================================================

If exception occurs:

lock()
...
exception
...
unlock() never called

Deadlock possible.

=========================================================
16. lock_guard
=========================================================

Preferred interview answer.

RAII wrapper around mutex.

void increment()
{
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

    counter++;
}

Automatically unlocks.

=========================================================
17. unique_lock
=========================================================

More flexible than lock_guard.

Supports:

- lock()
- unlock()
- try_lock()

Example:

std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

lock.unlock();

lock.lock();

=========================================================
18. lock_guard VS unique_lock
=========================================================

lock_guard
-----------
- Lightweight
- Fast
- Auto unlock
- Cannot unlock manually

unique_lock
------------
- More flexible
- Slightly heavier
- Can lock/unlock manually

Interview:
Use lock_guard when flexibility not needed.

=========================================================
19. DEADLOCK
=========================================================

Two threads waiting forever.

Thread1:

lock(m1)
lock(m2)

Thread2:

lock(m2)
lock(m1)

Both wait forever.

=========================================================
20. HOW TO AVOID DEADLOCK?
=========================================================

1. Lock mutexes in same order

2. Use std::lock()

3. Minimize lock duration

4. Use scoped locks

=========================================================
21. std::lock
=========================================================

std::lock(m1,m2);

Locks multiple mutexes safely.

=========================================================
22. SCOPED LOCK (C++17)
=========================================================

std::scoped_lock lock(m1,m2);

Safest way.

=========================================================
23. WHAT IS STARVATION?
=========================================================

Thread never gets CPU/resource because
others keep acquiring it.

=========================================================
24. WHAT IS LIVEOCK?
=========================================================

Threads keep changing state but
make no progress.

=========================================================
25. CONDITION VARIABLE
=========================================================

Used for thread communication.

One thread waits.

Another thread notifies.

Header:

#include <condition_variable>

=========================================================
26. WHY CONDITION VARIABLE?
=========================================================

Without it:

while(!ready)
{
}

Busy waiting.

Consumes CPU.

=========================================================
27. CONDITION VARIABLE EXAMPLE
=========================================================

std::mutex mtx;
std::condition_variable cv;

bool ready = false;

Thread A:

std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

cv.wait(lock, []{
    return ready;
});

Thread B:

{
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

    ready = true;
}

cv.notify_one();

=========================================================
28. notify_one()
=========================================================

Wakes one waiting thread.

=========================================================
29. notify_all()
=========================================================

Wakes all waiting threads.

=========================================================
